  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n- Initial reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. Major Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- UN Vienna Convention (1988)\n- Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced international cooperation frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Developments\n- Expanded criminal definitions\n- Stricter customer due diligence requirements\n- Enhanced transaction monitoring\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Advanced technological screening\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership regulations\n\n5. Global Compliance Frameworks\n- Enhanced international standards\n- Multilateral information exchange\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n- Comprehensive risk assessment protocols\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- AI-powered detection systems\n- Blockchain tracking mechanisms\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Advanced data analytics\n\nThe legislative landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial crime risks and technological challenges.",
